President Cyril Ramaphosa will lead the national celebration as South Africa marks 28 years of freedom and democracy.  MIDDELBURG - President Cyril Ramaphosa believes South Africans have tasted the fruits of freedom despite many saying there's not much to celebrate Ramaphosa addressed Freedom Day celebrations in Mpumalanga under the theme 'Consolidating Democratic Gains'. WATCH | Ramaphosa: Our people are tired of corruption He has spelled out that since democracy in 1994 many more South Africans have access to water, electricity and a home. But the president has also called on local and national governments to take a firm stance on corruption.  President Cyril Ramaphosa believes South Africans have tasted the fruits of freedom despite many saying there is not much to celebrate. He addressed #FreedomDay celebrations in Mpumalanga. #eNCA's @van1go is following this story. #DStv403 pic.twitter.com/10Rt4UpxZv